---
import "../styles/global.css";
import { ClientRouter } from "astro:transitions";
import Carousel from "../components/Carousel";
import Icon from "../components/Icon.astro";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg" />
    <link rel="icon" href="/favicon.ico" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width" />
    <meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
    <title>Astro</title>
    <ClientRouter />
  </head>
  <body class="flex flex-col" style="background-color: #f4f4f4;">
    <header class="flex justify-between px-6 py-4 items-center sticky top-0 z-10" style="background-color: #f4f4f4;">
      <div class="flex-1">
        <img src="/habitat-wordmark.svg" class="w-32" />
      </div>
      <nav class="flex text-lg gap-8">
        <a href="/users">For users</a>
        <a href="/developers">For developers</a>
      </nav>
      <div class="flex-1 flex justify-end gap-4 items-center">
        <a
          href="https://github.com/habitat-network/habitat"
          aria-label="GitHub"
        >
          <Icon name="github" class="w-6 h-6" />
        </a>
        <a href="https://bsky.app/profile/habitat.network" aria-label="Bluesky">
          <Icon name="bluesky" class="w-6 h-6" />
        </a>
        <a href="https://habitat.leaflet.pub" aria-label="Leaflet">
          <Icon name="leaflet" class="w-6 h-6" />
        </a>
      </div>
    </header>

    <main>
      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="section-1" class="relative min-h-screen flex flex-col justify-center overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute inset-y-0 left-0 w-2/3 -translate-x-1/3 pointer-events-none">
          <img src="/trees2.jpeg" class="h-full w-full object-cover object-right" alt="" />
          <div class="absolute inset-0" style="background: linear-gradient(to right, transparent 80%, #f4f4f4 100%), linear-gradient(to bottom, transparent 80%, #f4f4f4 100%);"></div>
        </div>
        <!-- Content shifted to the right -->
        <div class="relative flex flex-col items-start gap-16 py-16 pl-[45%] pr-12">
          <div class="prose max-w-3xl">
            <h1>We're building <b>user data agency</b> for the web.</h1>
            <p>
			Your data should be yours, forever. Not owned by companies to turn a profit. You shouldn't
           need to share your data with third-party servers in order to share it with
            the people you trust. We are laying the technical foundations to change the
            default settings of the web and break free from the cycle of data
            capture that currently exists online.
			

            </p>
          </div>
          <button
            onclick="document.getElementById('section-2').scrollIntoView({behavior: 'smooth', block: 'start'})"
            aria-label="Scroll to next section"
            class="transition-colors cursor-pointer" style="color: #217c3a;"
          >
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-8 h-8" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="section-2" class="min-h-screen flex flex-col items-center justify-center px-6 gap-16 py-16">
        <div class="prose">
          <h2>How habitat works</h2>
          <p>
            habitat provides a place where all your data lives and can be
            controlled by you. Developers build frontend apps, no third-party
            servers involved, so you can interact with that data how you
            normally would, but without sharing it with any other parties, keeping it safe from extraction and spying. This is
            all built on ATProtocol, a new open protocol for the social
            internet.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center gap-8 w-full">
          <div class="flex w-full max-w-5xl">
            <div class="flex-1 prose pr-52">
              <h3>The old way</h3>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1 prose pl-32">
              <h3>The habitat way</h3>
            </div>
          </div>
          <img src="/diagram.png" alt="Diagram" class="w-full max-w-8xl px-8" />
          <div class="flex w-full max-w-5xl">
            <div class="flex-1 prose pr-52">
              <p>
                Today, apps own the data you create with the app, and in order
                to share data with people, they need to use the same app. This
               	enables monopolies to build data moats that stifle competition
                while offering inferior experiences to users.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="flex-1 prose pl-32">
              <p>
                With habitat, you own your data and apps run locally on your device.
                Data is shared directly without involving third parties that can
                accumulate it. Apps are built to be compatible to leverage existing data to bring innovative
                user experiences.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="section-3" class="min-h-screen flex flex-col items-center justify-center px-6 gap-16 py-16">
        <div class="prose">
          <h2>
            Big Tech continues to harvest and steal our data.
          </h2>
		            <h3>We're actually doing something about it. </h3> 
        </div>
        <div class="not-prose">
          <Carousel
            client:load
            items={[
              { image: "/google.png", alt: "Google" },
              { image: "/grammarly.png", alt: "Grammarly" },
              { image: "/ring.png", alt: "Ring" },
			                { image: "/ibm.png", alt: "IBM" },
			                { image: "/meta.png", alt: "Meta" },

            ]}
          />
        </div>
        <div class="prose">
		   <p>
              Over the last decade, we've collectively
              experienced the internet get meaningfully... worse. Whether
              because of the attention economy, surveillance capitalism,
              enshittification, (or all the above and more), it's clear that the
              state of the web today isn't meant for us, for people. At the core
              of these issues lies data capture, through which Big Tech, data
              brokers, and surveillance dragnets have used our data against us.
              That's why to build a better web, we're trying
              to bring about user data ownership and agency at a protocol level.
          </p>
		  <h3>Sign up for the waitlist now.</h3>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>
